Shared Virtual Memory (SVM)¶

Shared Virtual Memory (SVM) in OpenCL is a way to blur or even erase the boundary between host memory and global device memory.

Sometimes algorithms can benefit when both host and device share access to the same memory. This may give the compute device access to larger memory allocations on the host. Compute device architectures such as System On Chip (SOC), where an integrated GPU uses host memory, is served well by SVM. Shared Virtual Memory is available on OpenCL 2.0+ implementations, and optionally available on OpenCL 3.0+ implementations.

Types of shared virtual memory¶

There are three main types of shared virtual memory (SVM):

  • Coarse-grained buffer SVM
  • Fine-grained buffer SVM
  • Fine-grained system SVM

Coarse-grained buffer SVM is the most basic level of SVM support and the only one that is technically required by the OpenCL 2.0 standard. Coarse-grained buffer SVM doesn't appear to be much different from standard OpenCL buffers. The only difference I can see is that it enables one to allocate and de-allocate memory on the host using special SVM functions clSVMAlloc and clSVMFree, and then the ability to use the allocated pointer in a kernel invocation instead of an OpenCL buffer. There may be synchronisation between host and device, however the allocation must still be mapped to the host for host access and then un-mapped when host access is no longer required.

Fine-grained buffer SVM removes the requirement to map and unmap memory, but it still needs the special SVM functions clSVMAlloc and clSVMFree to allocate and de-allocate shared memory. At runtime the code must notify the kernel of any SVM pointers that are to be used, either directly as kernel arguments or indirectly used (i.e through pointers in data structures accessed by the kernel). This can be extra work for the programmer. Unlike coarse-grained SVM, both host and device can access a fine-grained buffer at the same time. Consistency between host and device is guaranteed if host and device are writing to different bytes in the allocation. If there is a need for host and device to read what the other has written, then memory can be explicitly synchronised by waiting for the compute device to finish work on the buffer. If host and device must read and update the same bytes in the allocation, then atomic data types (if supported) and special synchronisation functions can be used to maintain coherency.

Fine-grained system SVM further removes the requirement to use clSVMAlloc and clSVMFree to allocate and de-allocate shared memory. System functions (such as malloc) allocate memory on the host, and the associated pointer is available for use in kernels. Only pointers directly used by the kernel must be passed in as kernel arguments. Pointers used indirectly can be accessed without having to notify the kernel of their existence. As with fine-grained buffer SVM, if host and device must read and update the same bytes in the allocation, then atomic data types (if supported) and special synchronisation functions can be used to maintain coherency.

Checking to see what kind of shared virtual memory your system supports¶

The OpenCL function clGetDeviceInfo can query the SVM capabilities of the compute device. In the file svm_check.cpp we use clGetDeviceInfo along with the key CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES to get a return code. The key CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES is only available with OpenCL 2.0+ implementations so the following code will not even compile with an old OpenCL implementation.

// Check if the device supports coarse-grained SVM
    cl_device_svm_capabilities svm;
    errcode = clGetDeviceInfo(
        device,
        CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES,
        sizeof(cl_device_svm_capabilities),
        &svm,
        NULL
    );

The error code may then be evaluated to see what SVM implementations are available:

if (errcode == CL_INVALID_VALUE) { 
        printf("Sorry, this device does not support Shared Virtual Memory.");
        exit(OCL_EXIT);
    }    

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_COARSE_GRAIN_BUFFER)) {
        printf("Device supports coarse-grained SVM\n");
    }

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained buffer SVM\n");
    }

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER) &&
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_ATOMICS)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained buffer SVM with atomics\n");
    }

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_SYSTEM)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained system SVM\n");
    }

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_SYSTEM) && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_ATOMICS)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained buffer SVM with atomics\n");
    }

Alternatively, the clinfo command is able to inspect what SVM implementations are available for each device. It is interesting to note that at the time of writing the Intel OpenCL implementation* has all forms of shared virtual memory available. The NVIDIA implementation only has coarse-grained SVM, and AMD has both coarse-grained and fine-grained SVM, but no support for SVM atomics.

In [1]:
!clinfo --prop SVM

[AMD/0]          CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES                      CL_DEVICE_SVM_COARSE_GRAIN_BUFFER | CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER
[NV/0]           CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES                      CL_DEVICE_SVM_COARSE_GRAIN_BUFFER
[INTEL/0]        CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES                      CL_DEVICE_SVM_COARSE_GRAIN_BUFFER | CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER | CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_SYSTEM | CL_DEVICE_SVM_ATOMICS

Coarse-grained SVM¶

For coarse-grained SVM we still have the restriction of having to map a memory space back to the host. The application mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp uses the standard matrix multiplication kernel.

Direct use of SVM allocations¶

We use clSVMAlloc to allocate Matrix C from coarse-grained shared virtual memory.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:165

    // Allocate coarse-grained SVM memory for C_svm
    cl_float *C_svm = (cl_float*)clSVMAlloc(
        context,
        CL_MEM_WRITE_ONLY,
        nbytes_C,
        0
    );

If the allocation fails, the pointer returned will be NULL. We can check for a valid alllocation with an assert statement.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:173

    // The memory allocation will return C_svm == NULL if allocation failed
    assert(C_svm!=NULL);

OpenCL kernels need to know that a memory allocation is shared with the host. At kernel launch we use a different function clSetKernelArgSVMPointer to set the kernel argument.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:197
   H_ERRCHK(clSetKernelArgSVMPointer(kernel, 2, C_svm));

As before, the memory in matrix C is used in the kernel mat_mult kernels_mat_mult.c just like any ordinary allocation.

// kernels_mat_mult.c:28 source

// standard matrix multiply kernel 
__kernel void mat_mult (__global float* A, 
                        __global float* B, 
                        __global float* C, 
                        unsigned int N1_A, 
                        unsigned int N0_C,
                        unsigned int N1_C) {
    ...

Coarse-grained SVM requires explicit synchronisation. In order to use the allocation from the host it must be mapped. Here we map array_C back to the host with clEnqueueSVMMap, write the memory to storage, and unmap with clEnqueueSVMUnmap.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:265

    // Map the SVM array to the host, 
    // this synchronises C_svm to the host
    H_ERRCHK(
        clEnqueueSVMMap(
            command_queue,
            CL_TRUE,
            CL_MAP_READ,
            C_svm,
            nbytes_C,
            1,
            &kernel_event,
            NULL
        )
    );

    //// Step 11. Test the answer against a known solution
    //// And write the contents of the matrices out to disk

    // Compute the serial solution using the matrix helper library
    float* C_answer_h = (float*)calloc(nbytes_C, 1);
    m_mat_mult(A_h, B_h, C_answer_h, N1_A, N0_C, N1_C);

    // Print the maximum error between matrices
    float max_err = m_max_error(C_svm, C_answer_h, N0_C, N1_C);

    // Write out the host arrays to file
    h_write_binary(A_h, "array_A.dat", nbytes_A);
    h_write_binary(B_h, "array_B.dat", nbytes_B);
    h_write_binary(C_svm, "array_C.dat", nbytes_C);

    //// Step 12. Clean up arrays and release resources

    // Unmap the SVM array from the host
    H_ERRCHK(
        clEnqueueSVMUnmap(
            command_queue,
            C_svm,
            0,
            NULL,
            NULL
        )
    );

Now that the memory is unmapped we can use either clSVMFree or clEnqueueSVMFree to free the allocation. It might be preferred to use clEnqueueSVMFree because the free is enqueued to a command queue and you can be certain the command queue is empty before freeing memory.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:306

    // Enqueue a free of the SVM buffer C_svm
    H_ERRCHK(
        clEnqueueSVMFree(
            command_queue,
            1,
            (void**)((void*)(&C_svm)),
            NULL,
            NULL,
            0,
            NULL,
            NULL
        )
    );

SVM pointers as a backing store for a buffer¶

Another way to use coarse-grained SVM is to allocate the memory with clSVMAlloc and then overlay a Buffer on it using the CL_MEM_ALLOC_HOST_PTR flag. We do this for matrix A in mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:133 

    // Using coarse-grained SVM memory
    // Allocate backing storage (A_svm) for A_d
    cl_float *A_svm = (cl_float*)clSVMAlloc(
            context,
            CL_MEM_READ_WRITE,
            nbytes_A,
            0
    );

    // Wrap an OpenCL buffer around the SVM allocation A_svm
    cl_mem A_d = clCreateBuffer(
            context, 
            CL_MEM_READ_WRITE | CL_MEM_USE_HOST_PTR, 
            nbytes_A, 
            A_svm, 
            &errcode
    );
    H_ERRCHK(errcode);

If we overlay a buffer on the SVM allocation then we must release the buffer before deallocating the underlying storage.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:323 

    H_ERRCHK(clReleaseMemObject(A_d));

Then we can free the SVM pointer, this time we use clSVMFree to deallocate because we waited on the kernel to finish and know that A_d has been released.

// mat_mult_coarse_buffer_svm.cpp:324 

    // Free backing storage for A_d, note that A_d has been released
    clSVMFree(context, A_svm);

Fine-grained buffer SVM¶

Fine-grained buffer SVM dispenses with the need for explicit mapping and unmapping steps that were necessary in coarse-grained buffer SVM. Synchronisation for a buffer is guaranteed when we know a kernel is finished with the memory, such as after calls to clFinish or clWaitForEvents. In the file mat_mult_fine_buffer_svm.cpp We check for fine_grained_buffer_SVM using the CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER flag.

// mat_mult_fine_buffer_svm.cpp:89
    // Check if the device supports fine-grained buffer SVM
    cl_device_svm_capabilities svm;
    errcode = clGetDeviceInfo(
        device,
        CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES,
        sizeof(cl_device_svm_capabilities),
        &svm,
        NULL
    );

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained buffer SVM\n");
    } else {
        printf("Sorry, this device can not support fine-grained buffer SVM\n");
        printf("No solution performed\n");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

Now that we have checked for fine-grained support, then we allocate SVM memory for matrix C with an additional CL_MEM_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER flag to let the implementation know we want fine-grained synchronisation for the buffer.

// mat_mult_fine_buffer_svm.cpp:165
    // Allocate SVM memory for array C using a fine-grained buffer
    cl_float *C_svm = (cl_float*)clSVMAlloc(
        context,
        CL_MEM_WRITE_ONLY | CL_MEM_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER,
        nbytes_C,
        0
    );

    // mat_mult_fine_buffer_svm.cpp:173

    // The memory allocation will return C_svm == NULL if allocation failed
    assert(C_svm!=NULL);

Fine-grained system SVM¶

With fine-grained system SVM we

  • Don't need a call to clSVMAlloc to allocate shared memory,
  • Don't need to create and destroy OpenCL buffers,
  • Don't need to explicitly copy memory between host and device.

What a beautiful thing! Unfortunately support for fine-grained system SVM is not common amongst OpenCL implementations. At the time of writing only the Intel implementation supports it. Hopefully this will change in future!

The source code in mat_mult_fine_system_svm.cpp contains the fine-grained system SVM implementation for matrix multiplication. We check for fine-grain system SVM in a similar fashion to fine-grain buffer SVM.

// mat_mult_fine_system_svm.cpp:90

    // Check if the device supports fine-grained system SVM
    cl_device_svm_capabilities svm;
    errcode = clGetDeviceInfo(
        device,
        CL_DEVICE_SVM_CAPABILITIES,
        sizeof(cl_device_svm_capabilities),
        &svm,
        NULL
    );

    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_SYSTEM)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained system SVM\n");
    } else {
        printf("Sorry, this device can not support fine-grained system SVM\n");
        printf("No solution performed\n");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

Any C function, such as malloc or calloc may be used to allocate memory for A_h, B_h and C_h. Here we use an aligned memory allocation to mitigate any potential issues with alignment.

// mat_mult_fine_system_svm.cpp:118

    // Number of bytes in each array
    size_t nbytes_A = N0_C*N1_A*sizeof(cl_float);
    size_t nbytes_B = N1_A*N1_C*sizeof(cl_float);
    size_t nbytes_C = N0_C*N1_C*sizeof(cl_float);

    // Allocate memory for matrices A, B, and C on the host
    cl_float* A_h = (cl_float*)h_alloc(nbytes_A);
    cl_float* B_h = (cl_float*)h_alloc(nbytes_B);
    cl_float *C_h = (cl_float*)h_alloc(nbytes_C);

We can use A_h, B_h, and C_h directly as arguments to the kernel. We just need to use the clSetKernelArgSVMPointer function to let the kernel know the allocation is shared memory.

// mat_mult_fine_system_svm.cpp:135

    H_ERRCHK(clSetKernelArgSVMPointer(kernel, 0, A_h));
    H_ERRCHK(clSetKernelArgSVMPointer(kernel, 1, B_h));
    H_ERRCHK(clSetKernelArgSVMPointer(kernel, 2, C_h));

Fine-grained SVM with atomics¶

There are atomic operations to synchronise memory between the host and fine-grained SVM buffers, howewer the OpenCL implementation needs to support it. The additional flag CL_DEVICE_SVM_ATOMICS (for example as checked for in in svm_check.cpp) is the flag to look for when looking for SVM atomics support.

// svm_check.cpp:83 
    if (errcode == CL_SUCCESS && 
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_FINE_GRAIN_BUFFER) &&
        (svm & CL_DEVICE_SVM_ATOMICS)) {
        printf("Device supports fine-grained buffer SVM with atomics\n");
    }

At this stage it seems that SVM atomics for fine-grained synchronisation between host and device is ready for inclusion in production code. The documentation on what SVM atomics actually are is sparse and support for CL_DEVICE_SVM_ATOMICS only seems to be available with the Intel OpenCL implementations.
